<subSubSection id="0F11C66AA419F52F2A1CF1B43852C9E7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="CB130E681485293C3DB23F103427F673" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="519678F88E3E0DD12A9DB63E714F72E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species appears to have evolved as an adaptation of 
<taxonomicName id="771B9164689297BB4436A98DDABEDDAE" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="indica">
<emphasis id="96FD2A4855A3FD4B66E1F61BC5D9DA62" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for humming bird pollination. It differs in the exserted stamens from a salver-shaped corolla as well as in the leaves, which are always three lobed.
</paragraph>
